title: OpenSCAD League Gothic Proportional Font Module

description.text: A version of http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:6820 that simplifies the proportional placement of the characters.

http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:6820 did all the hard work here. I've just added an extra parameter to the function that positions each individual character at the place you specify in an array. So instead of... fnt_str(["H","e","l","l","o"],5,1,3); You can now use... fnt_str_p(["H","e","l","l","o"], [0,5,10,15,20], 5,1,3); The second array specifies the positions of the characters. The above two function calls would produce the same results because the array of positions passed in is mono spaced. You can now manually adjust the values of the position array to space the characters as you choose. I've defined some variables that represent the widths of the various characters. You can add these variables together to get the absolute position of the characters as follows... fnt_str_p(["H","e","l","l","o"],
[0,
HH,
HH+ee,
HH+ee+ll,
HH+ee+ll+ll],
5,1,3); It's incredibly ugly but as the language doesn't support local variables or recursion I haven't managed to think of a neater way. example.scad was used to create the main image. I had to adjust the syntax of OpenSCADFont.scad slightly to work on Windows. There are some missing files as : is an invalid character for filenames in Windows. I'd welcome any comments on improvements.

Printing and assembly tips

Printing tips
1-As with most of my models, no supports are required.

2-The arms are tall with a small base, so I used a brim on those two pieces.

3-Be sure to clean any first layer squish if you have any problem joining parts. The parts should fit nicely when printed cleanly or with a slight first layer squish.

..
Assembly tips:

1-The left/right eyes and eyebrows are interchangeable.

2-The leg holes in the pants should be positioned toward the back.

3-The left/right shoe parts are not interchangeable but are easy to distinguish which is left and right.

4-The left right pieces of the sleeves of the shirt are NOT interchangeable, so take some care in placing them before gluing.

5-When putting the shirt together the holes for the shirt pin is positioned towards the back. The side of each shirt part that was on the printer bed will always face down as you slide each piece through the shirt_pin. Similarly, when sliding the arm pieces on to the shirt_black_6 piece (which acts as a pin) the side that was on the printer bed will face the body.

6-The hair is quite simple. It is printed flat. After removing it from the printer bed, you need to curl each individual hair similar to how you would curl a ribbon. Be sure to curl the all the hair strands in the same direction and start from the 'root'. This results in what looks like spider legs. Position the root in the back/top of the head and adjust for the desired look as you glue it down. There is no 'notch' to be matched.

6-I glued the head/blanket/arm_left all in together to the body at the same time. The blanket does not necessarily need to touch the ground. I did it this way to ensure the model stands stable on the shoes and the blanket does not cause any balancing issue.

*Refer to the assembly diagrams in the pictures section for putting the model together. (for some unknown reason I cannot load the assembly diagrams in the narrative section). The model is meant to be glued.

description.text: This a vise created for a 3D printer class competition. It was printed using the Tronxy X3A. It consists of a 3D printed fixed jaw base, sliding jaw, detachable grips, screw knob, and base plate. The vise uses a 4” long ¼-20 bolt, nut, and washer. I wrapped the head of the ¼-20 bolt with modeling tape and pressed the head of the bolt into the recessed portion of the screw knob. I deliberately oversized the recess on the knob, and wrapping the bolt head ensured a tight fit on the knob. I then installed the bolt in the fixed jaw base, with a washer placed between the knob and the fixed jaw base to ensure smooth operation. I then attached the sliding jaw. The jaw has a recess printed into the jaw to install the ¼-20 nut. The nut is used to pull the sliding jaw towards the fixed jaw base as the screw knob is turned; recessing the nut into the part captures the nut and doesn’t allow it to freespin within the part. I wrapped the nut with modeling tape to ensure a tight fit in the recess, and made sure that the nut aligned with the holes in the sliding jaw before running the bolt through. After tightening the knob, I was able to bring the sliding jaw into the fixed jaw base. I then superglued the fixed jaw base to the base plate. The base plate has a raised stopper plate which keeps the bolt from sliding in the clamp. It has enough space between the stopper and the knob to maintain smooth operation. The base plate also has mount points using ¼-20 bolts at 1” centers. After I installed the base plate I installed the detachable grips into the fixed jaw base and sliding jaw. These grips have dovetail joints and can be redesigned to meet the user’s needs.

description.text:
I've got a bad habit of knocking over my Red Bull cans while at work, plus I'm tired of having to check to see if any bugs flew into my drink before sipping.

I printed this in TPU to make sure it'd slide over the lip and stay on in case of a tip. You can try other filaments, but you may have to scale it up, and I'm not sure even then how well it'll handle.

Note: the original test prints I did with SainSmart TPU (green), but tried some unknown name brand (red/black) for a two-tone print. The supports on the first were easy to remove, the black one, not so much. I got most of it cleared, though, and it still works. So, if you can put your own supports in (such as with Simplify3D), I'd recommend it.

Edit: Finally scaled one up for the 12oz Red Bull can as well. The green one is the 8.4oz, and the blue is the 12oz version.

description.text:
This mount was designed for the ender 2 for use with a flebay dial indicator (link below) and 6mm x 3mm round neodymium magnets (link to some below although it is also possible to buy them in smaller quantities). It makes the job of bed levelling a lot easier!

My process is as follows,

  • heat bed and nozzle to desired temp
  • run though the ender 2's "auto bed level" function, I just click through to the fifth point which should the mid point of the bed in both x and y.
  • use a feeler gauge to level the bed at 0.01mm (this depends on the offset you use in your slicer of choice)
  • raise the z to 30mm
  • install the gauge using the right angle protrusion to index it and "zero"
  • run the gauge in x and y to determine levelness of the bed and adjust (I aim for a variance of around 0.02mm throughout the bed, easy to achieve and sufficient for the 0.2mm first layers I normally print)
  • REMOVE the gauge before printing

Please note I have deigned the mount to be about to stick to both the "front" and "right side" of the hotend case. This allows for testing of most of the bed surface. I normally use it on the "front" to test the x axis and on the "right side" to test the y axis.

Enjoy and please let me know if you print this helpful little device!

This is a full enclosure for the SeeMeCNC Rostock Max V2.
It has double doors on all three sides that swing open fully allowing easy access to the build area.

I designed this enclosure to create a heated chamber and to (hopefully) capture the noxious fumes from ABS printing. It was created using the CAD files for the printer that are available on the SeeMeCNC GitHub.

To make your own enclosure you will need:

  • 3 bottom pieces, 3 top pieces, 6 middle pieces, and 6 spacers

  • Clear acrylic: There are 6 door pieces and 3 fixed pieces, 15 hinges, and 6 handles. I took measurements to a local plastics dealer and had them cut for me. They also sold the hinges, door handles, and glue.

  • Rare earth magnets: Size: 3/8" x 1/10" Qty: 24 I bought mine here. These are installed into the middle pieces through a hold in the bottom BEFORE installing on the printer.

  • 18 screws and Tee nuts as well as a drill to make holes in the bottom and top of the printer to attach the printer parts. I took one of the screws from the bottom middle of the printer to the hardware store to ensure that they matched.

After the parts are printed you will need to install them. The bottom corner pieces as well as all 6 pieces on the top attach using the screws mentioned above. The 3 middle pieces on the bottom attach using the screws that are already in the printer. When drilling the holes make sure that they are in the right place. A few of the holes on my printer are a bit oversized now because I didn't get it right the first time.

Once the printed parts are mounted you can take measurements for the acrylic pieces and have them cut to size.

Now make 6 long hinges from the 15 short ones. There are longer hinges available that use a flexible strip of rubber instead of the traditional hinges that I show in the pictures. I tried those first and had to scrap them. The flexible rubber just isn't flexible enough. Holfing the doors closed was difficult and they didn't want to stay open. Esentially, the doors were always in my way. This was an expensive mistake for me.
Start by cutting 3 of the hinges in half. Once done you will notice that the hinge rod can fall out of one of the halves. Put a drop of glue on one end of the hinge rod after making sure that it is alligned.
Now carefully glue 2 and a half hinges together using a straight edge to ensure that they are alligned.

The next step is to glue it all together. Install the 6 spacers on the verticle arms of the printer with 2 on each arm evenly spaced. Install and center the 3 fixed panels. Use 2 business cards to create a space between 2 door panels and tape them together. Tape the other door panels together in the same manner and then center and tape them to the printer.

Allign a hinge on the bottom edge of the acrylic and tape it to the enclosure. Do this for all 6 hinges. You will notice that the hinge is too long. This is OK as you will cut it to the correct length later.

Now comes the tricky part. Carufully apply glue to each hinge ONLY WHERE SUPPORTED BY A SPACER OR THE TOP AND BOTTOM. The acrylic will flex if you press on it while glueing. If it is not supported it will create a bend in the plastic that will make the hinges flex while in use. Trust me, you don't want this to happen.

After the hinges have been tacked at the top, bottom, and by each of the 2 spacers remove the 3 acrylic parts by carefully flexing them out of the top and bottom holders. Once out, pleace them on a flat surface and glue the hinges alont their full lenght, cut the hinges to length, and reinstall on the printer. Make sure that the 3 acrylic pieces go back into the same place on the printer. They are not identical and if you install them in the wrong order the doors will not close properly.

Now you just need to add handles and the magnets on the doors.

That's it. Easy, right?
This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/bEGs0RgEXR3

description.text: I love my Bugs 3 but I also crash a lot. One of my rear arms broke and from what I'm seeing online the arms always seem to break in the same location. Luckily for us, we can purchase new frames online for around 12 bucks but my issue is that I will need to wait a month for the frame to arrive. I am an impatient bastard so I fired up my Fusion360 and created this replacement arm that can be bolted to the stock frame after you cut off the stock arms. If my new arms break again you will no longer need to unsolder the motors to replace them. Print 4 of these top facing down so the supports are easier to remove. I used natural color PLA so I'm hoping that the lights look cool at night shining through the arms. Do not use the stock screws for the tall landing gear to hold in these arms. During testing after aggressively flying 3 packs, one of the arms came loose causing the propeller to hit the body causing the whole thing to fall to the ground. All arms broke in the same location as the stock arms do. I am going to print 4 more and put larger screws, perhaps with a nut to keep this from happening again. It flew great up until the arm came loose. Check out my photos carefully to see where I did the cutting on the arms, basically just were the smooth underbelly stops. I used a hacksaw for the cutting and a razor blade to remove the plastic bits to make room for the wiring. Weight after modifications without the battery is 342 grams, slightly heavier but still not nearly as heavy as carrying a GoPro so it still flies great. Enjoy.

title: Kossel oven bag heat enclosure tent

description.text: Heat enclosure for the Kossel Mini, made from cheap oven bags and chopsticks.

Making the Heat Bag

Rather than creating a large plastic box to encase my Kossel, I hit on the idea of using oven roasting bags. Oven bags are typically rated up to temperatures of 200C and even the large ones are pretty cheap.

Joining them together to make a large bag to cover your printer is pretty simple. First cut them open into flat sheets. Then melt them together into a single large bag.

To join them, lay two sheets flat on top of one another, then using your soldering iron (preferably with a flat cutting tip), run it along the edge. Too slow and it won't melt, too fast and it'll melt away too much and make a hole. Just practise and you'll find a speed that works.

In the images, I made a flat rectangular bag, but I plan on buying more oven bags and making a perfectly fitting triangular prism.

title: RFlink case with Antennas and NodeMCU support

description.text:
[Edit 17/11/17]
Added a new top version, where the NodeMCU is positionned on the center, so that the pin of the NodeMCU and the pin of the Mega2560 are out of line, making usage of dupont plugs more easy to position.
[/Edit]

RFlink is an awesome tool to make home automation.
In addition to a NodeMCU, the device can be anywhere in the house where the RF signal can be optimum. The NodeMCU can be used in two ways to make it network-enabled:

  • Use ESP Esay to implement a ser2net solution. This is the best solution for Domoticz.
  • Use a Homie-based MQTT gateway, like this excellent one: https://github.com/enc-X/mqtt-rflink-bridge
    This is the best I found for OpenHab integration.

The case improve the initial design by adding:

  • Support Antenna to hold standard 17.3 cm wire from SYN115. The antennas are screwable into the 2 holes, can be removed for transport.
  • Support and maintain a 3.3V/5V level shifter
  • Support standard NodeMCU V1.0

Antennas are fully printable, but better use a brim or a raft to maintain them during printing. For screws, I used the same as those needed to maintain Cdrom in a PC, the size is just perfect.

For enc-X-mqtt-gateway, I used D3 and D4 for serial communication on the NodeMCU, when connected to RX and TX pin, Arduino IDE cannot upload the sketch. The line shoudl then be modified like this:
modify: #define PIN_SOFT_SERIAL_RX D3 //D3
and #define PIN_SOFT_SERIAL_TX D4 //D4

Only plug a micro-usb PSU to the NodeMCU, the Mega2560 is powered from the NodeMCU, the Mega USB port is only accessible to allow firmware update and should not be used otherwize.
Fusion 360 rocks !

title: Motorized bogie for OS-Railway - fully 3D-printable railway system

description.text:
This is a new version of the motorized bogie for the Hectorrail 141. I decided to publish it on a separate page because this bogie can be used to create custom locomotives.

Main difference from original version is that the main frame is divided to make assembly much easier, and the connecting shaft is 3mm as well as the wheel shafts. The frame also has room for ball bearings of the same size (6mm OD, 3mm ID, 2.5mm T) that is used for the wheels. However, the frame is made so that you don't have to have the ball bearings installed. Because of the printing process, you might need to drill the hole for this shaft a bit as there are several edges that needs to have enough clearance.

This page includes two motor mounts, one for 16mm motors and gearbox that has long shafts (Maxon DCX16 with GPX16), and one for motor+gearbox with short shaft.

The motor mount slides on the main frame, and you will most likely have to use substantial force to get it in position, but this way it will sit much tighter than the old design and there is no screws in the way of the drive gears. Instead, the locking plate is fastened with 4pcs M2x10-12.

Hardware needed

Connecting shaft: 3mm thickness 39-40mm length
Wheel shafts: 3mm thickness 44mm length (2pcs/bogie)
Distance between inner side of wheels: 28mm
Screws holding center hub: M3x18 (2pcs / bogie)
Screw holding bogie to locomotive: M3x20

Included in the package are both wheels with slots for O-rings, meant for the driving bogie, but also a flat wheel as you can build the same bogie without any gears or motor mount and use as the non-motorized bogie.

Link to the Hectorrail 141 locomotive: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2575667

More related designs: https://www.thingiverse.com/groups/os-railway/things

These new files will also be uploaded to the Hectorrail 141.

description.text:
These are designs for a Bernoulli gripper. The designs differ only in the thread types and pipe sizes and are labeled as such. The cream color device is the design that I uploaded. The black device that was being tested in the pictures is an older model. If you have a 1/2inch airgun nozzle, the most common thread layout is 20 threads per inch and if you have a 3/8inch nozzle, you will likely have 24 threads per inch. But, it was easy to add both thread layouts so I did that just in case.

A Bernoulli gripper creates a lift force by using the Bernoulli effect (how airplanes create lift to ascend). By forcing air out of the openings parallel to the surface you want to grip, a low pressure region is created above the surface that pulls the object to grip towards the gripper. You essentially create a vacuum by pushing air out very quickly. Bernoulli grippers are not conventionally accessible to the average human as they can range in price from $500 to $2000. I needed one for some experiments at work and so I designed and printed one for cheap! I don't have a printer so mbailly printed my prototypes: Thanks to mbailly!

Bernoulli grippers have found applications ranging from moving delicate objects such as silicon wafers (see pics) to wall climbing robots. Bernoulli grippers are favored over vacuums for the latter application because they can grip porous and even perforated sheets, whereas vacuums would fail.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=phSlc8B4kFo

The air pressure required to run these devices must remain constant anywhere between 7 and 40psi depending on the weight of the object and how close you set the object from gripper. The set distance is created by the neoprene or rubber bumpers. The less the bumpers protrude the better! It will take less work to lift the device.These devices are really cool and I hope you have fun finding applications for this.

Step 1. Cut out the neoprene and push it through the bottom as shown. Try to leave as little neoprene protruding as possible. Remember, the neoprene's only purpose is to act as a barrier to lateral movement by using friction. The farther the neoprene protrudes, the harder the air pump has to work and the smaller the lift force is felt by the object to be gripped. Step 2. Pretty straightforward. Fill 'er up with hot glue. If you think your neoprene protrusions are uneven, you can push gently down in this position to try and even them out before applying glue.

title: Y Belt Tensioner for Anet A6

description.text:
Maybe my Anet A6 is slightly different dimensionally than other peoples, but none of the belt tensioners I tried worked quite right. There were some clever designs, but things were not quite in proper alignment. So, I reworked and combined two existing tensioner designs. I also added my own part to help it stay in place. Plus, I included a spacer remix I used to get the belt running at the proper height.

  • I reworked NicktheGeek's design so that the idle pulley axle on the tensioner was at the same height as the Y stepper motor axle. This gets the bottom length of the belt loop to run parallel to the Y-axis bearing rods.
  • I also changed the position of the tensioning knob so that it pushed on the end of the printer at the same height as the idle pulley axle. This reduces/prevents any twisting or pivoting of the tensioning mechanism as you adjust it, or as the heat plate moves.
  • I used the larger knob from MrPaulM design to give me a larger pushing surface for stability. I compressed the knob down so the threads were tighter pitch, so you get more adjustment resolution.
  • I added a clip to retain the knob and plate in position. While I was testing the design, I swung my elbow and knocked the knob and plate out, loosening the belt and ruining my test print. Oops! That convinced me I needed something to make sure they stay in place when under tension.
  • For my A6, I needed a 17mm spacer to lower the belt connection on the heated plate (so that the top length of the belt loop runs parallel to the Y-axis bearing rods.) I took andreas_g's existing spacer and made it 17mm tall. If you do not already have a spacer of some type on your printer for this purpose, you need it to get the best results from the tensioner, and your printer in general. If you're using something else already, that's fine, don't use the part I have here. To mount the belt spacer, you'll need 4x 4Mx30mm bolts.

12-25-17
Updated the belt spacer file. It had a minor glitch in the STL. If you have the original one, you may have to drill-out the two of the mounting holes.

This vise can be configured in a lot of different ways. It can turn 360 degrees around while being extended out a few inches. The extender can be removed and the vise can then be placed straight up or on its side directly on the base and then each of these configurations can be rotated 360 degrees. It can be locked at almost any angle (see pictures).

Details:

There is a large version and a small version of the vise. The large version is 200 mm wide for the largest dimension of any part.
The small version is half the size of the large version in every dimension.
The files are separated by name with "small_" appended to the filename on the small version.

I increased the nose length of the clamps on the small vise from the pictures and made the vise open wider by making the Clamp Arm longer. As part of this change on the small vise, I made new clamp sleeves that fit this larger size (removable jaw plates). You obviously need to print two of these sleeves, one for each side.
I also widened the clampArm hole on the main part of the small vise to make it easier to assemble and hopefully avoid sanding.

Instructions:

I cut the all thread to lengths I needed. You can use a Dremel or something similar (or an old school hacksaw). You will need to print two of the bolt_tube pieces (not the best name). They hold a nut captive. They are joined together around the nut and then tapped into the small hole on the side of the vise. The all-thread is then run down the length of the moving clamp arm and into the captive nut (put the two nuts on while running it through --discussed in a minute). I let the all-thread go all the way to the end of the inside of the clamp arm after running it through the captive nut.
The other end is cut to the length that allows for the wheel_washer and the wheel to mount to the end. These are tightened to act like the end of a bolt where they will turn the all-thread. Just put the captive nut in each one and turn each in opposite directions to lock them together.
Two nuts are tightened in opposite directions just on the inside of the clamp arm. These are used to allow the vise to come back open. I put a drop of super glue on the threads to make sure that the nuts always turn with the all-thread and don’t back out (don’t do this until you are sure it is together correctly). Make sure these are close to the wheel side of the clamp arm to avoid unnecessary slop.
The knobs are used to lock the vise in place around the cylinders. They each have a captive nut and the all-thread is cut just long enough to reach the cylinders. If you have trouble getting the nut snug into the hole, just put the all-thread through the hole, twist on the nut, and then use another nut on the other side of the knob and a crescent wrench to tighten the nut into the hole.
There are also clip-on jaw plates for the large vise and slide-on jaws for the small vise (These jaw plates are not shown in the pictures).
The first time things go together, some sanding may be necessary. Once you get the clamp arm into the base, you just have to slide it back and forth a bunch to get things to where they slide in and out easily. This assures a nice tight fit.

description.text:
This is a pet bowl handle that can be used by folks with back problems. It allows you to access the bowls for refilling/cleaning without bending over.

I used a $3.99 plastic double pet bowl from Target, a $2 1/4"x20 threaded rod (24"-36" length depending on preference) and two 1/4"x20 nuts.

Assembly:

  1. Drill a 1/4" hole near the intersection of the wall and divider.
  2. Screw the 1/4"x20 threaded rod into the pyramid base. The base has a 6mm hole while will allow it to grip the 1/4" rod very firmly.

  4. Thread first nut and make sure is securely holds the rod in place. Test the bowl to make sure it doesn't tip over.
  5. Add 2nd 1/4x20 nut and use two wrenches to lock the nuts together.
  6. Screw the sphere knob on to the top of the threaded rod. The knob has a 6mm hole which will allow it to grip the 1/4" threaded rod very firmly.

description.text: In trying to improve my Original Prusa MK1 3D printer, I have purchased a real E3D V6 Full extruder upgrade. To house the E3D V6 Full, I have initially used the Prusa MK2 extruder parts. But I was not satisfied, so I have decided to improve on the MK2 extruder parts design. My initial goal was to improve visibility of the parts on the bed and this has resulted in other improvements. I have rotate the filament feeding section 90 degrees to the left side and I have move the cooling fan to the right side clearing the front of the extruder. I have improved the filament feeding section to improve the access and visibility of the filament. I have also introduced a fan ducking system to better cool the object with minimal heat loss on the bed. It does fit on the original MK1/MK2 X-carriage unmodified. All this being done using the same motor, fans and less nuts, bolts and parts compared to the Original Prusa MK2 design. I have done the testing on my MK1, but I believe it should work on a MK2 also. Have fun.

Definitely need support for the jaw and the handle. Maybe for the drawthing; I skipped it due to oversight when setting up Cura and it printed okay.

Five STL files, designed in FreeCAD. The jaw needs to be printed twice. Might seem wrong to have two identical jaws, but when they’re turned around to face each other it all fits right. I printed the jaws lying on their backs and then had to clean up the back of the jaws where support left a finish rougher than I’d like. Support leaves a rough surface on the back of the spring, too, but I found it best to leave it as is. Cleaning up changed the springiness.
